Diagram 2 (A Pae Again)
[{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg949\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset129 \'b1\'bc\'b8\'b2;}{\f1\fmodern\fprq2\fcharset129 \'b1\'bc\'b8\'b2;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\lang1042\f0\fs18
\par White 1 is a formidable move.
\par However, after black connects at 2, no matter where white plays, a pae is unavoidable.
\par
\par For example, if white plays at 3, black plays 4, creating a pae.
\par \pard\nowidctlpar\qj Instead of 3, it appears to be a good move for white to play at 4, but when black plays a throw-in at \b\f1 A\b0\f0 , it also becomes a pae.
\par }
